}}\n{{JME}}\n\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:Island Records singles]]\n[[Category:Jme (MC) songs]]\n[[Category:KSI (entertainer) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by KSI]]\n[[Category:YouTube music videos]]\n", "name_user": "Timwikisidemen", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep_Up_(KSI_song)"}
{"title_page": "Buridan's ass", "text_new": "[[Image:Deliberations of Congress.jpg|thumb|Political cartoon c.&nbsp;1900, showing the [[United States Congress]] as Buridan's ass (the two hay piles version), hesitating between a [[Panama Canal|Panama route]] or a [[Nicaragua Canal|Nicaragua route]] for an [[History of the Panama Canal|Atlantic\u2013Pacific canal]].]]\n\n'''Buridan's ass''' is an illustration of a [[paradox]] in philosophy in the conception of [[free will]].\nIt refers to a hypothetical situation wherein a [[donkey]] that is equally hungry and thirsty is placed precisely midway between a stack of hay and a pail of water. Since the paradox assumes the ass will always go to whichever is closer, it dies of both hunger and thirst since it cannot make any rational decision between the hay and water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O214-Buridansass.html |title=Buridan's ass: Oxford Companion to Phrase and Fable |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=2009-12-15}}</ref> A common variant of the paradox substitutes two identical piles of hay for the hay and water; the ass, unable to choose between the two, dies of hunger.\n\nThe paradox is named after the 14th-century [[France|French]] [[philosopher]] [[Jean Buridan]], whose philosophy of moral [[determinism]] it satirizes. \nAlthough the illustration is named after Buridan, philosophers have discussed the concept before him, notably [[Aristotle]] who used the example of a man equally hungry and thirsty,<ref name=\"Rescher\" /> and [[Al-Ghazali]] who used a man faced with the choice of equally good [[date (fruit)|dates]].<ref name=Kane/>\n\nA version of this situation appears as [[metastability in electronics|metastability]] in digital electronics, when a circuit must decide between two states based on an input that is in itself undefined (neither zero nor one).  Metastability becomes a problem if the circuit spends more time than it should in this \"undecided\" state, which is usually set by the speed of the clock the system is using.\n\n==History==\n\nThe paradox predates Buridan; it dates to antiquity, being found in [[Aristotle]]'s ''[[On the Heavens]]''.<ref name=\"Rescher\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Rescher\n  | first = Nicholas \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Cosmos and Logos: Studies in Greek Philosophy\n  | publisher = Ontos Verlag\n  | date = 2005\n  | location = \n  | pages = 93\u201399\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=qU3MdvVlvpAC&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=aristotle+%22buridan's+ass%22#v=onepage&q=aristotle%20%22buridan's%20ass%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 393720265X}}</ref>  Aristotle, in ridiculing the [[Sophist]] idea that the Earth is stationary simply because it is spherical and any forces on it must be equal in all directions, says that is as ridiculous as saying that:<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n{{Quotation|...a man, being just as hungry as thirsty, and placed in between food and drink, must necessarily remain where he is and starve to death.|Aristotle, ''On the Heavens'' 295b, c. 350 BC }}\nHowever, the Greeks only used this paradox as an analogy in the context of the equilibrium of ''physical'' forces.<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n\nThe 12th-century Persian scholar and philosopher [[al-Ghazali]] discusses the application of this paradox to human decision making, asking whether it is possible to make a choice between equally good courses without grounds for preference.<ref name=\"Rescher\" /> He takes the attitude that free will can break the stalemate.\n{{Quotation|Suppose two similar dates in front of a man, who has a strong desire for them but who is unable to take them both. Surely he will take one of them, through a quality in him, the nature of which is to differentiate between two similar things.|[[Al-Ghazali|Abu Hamid al-Ghazali]], ''[[The Incoherence of the Philosophers]]'', c.  1100<ref name=Kane>{{cite book |last=Kane |first=Robert |title=A Contemporary Introduction to Free Will |year=2005 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York|pages=37}}</ref>}}\nMoorish philosopher [[Averroes]] (1126\u20131198), in commentary on Ghazali, takes the opposite view.<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n\nAlthough Buridan nowhere discusses this specific problem, its relevance is that he did advocate a moral determinism whereby, save for ignorance or impediment, a human faced by alternative courses of action must always choose the greater [[good (economics)|good]]. In the face of equally good alternatives Buridan believed a rational choice could not be made.<ref name=\"Kinniment\">{{cite book     | last = Kinniment  | first = David J.   | authorlink =   | title = Synchronization and Arbitration in Digital Systems  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons  | date = 2008  | location =   | pages = 3  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_1p-BA4yriIC&pg=PA3\n  | doi =   | isbn = 978-0470517130}}</ref> \n{{Quotation|Should two courses be judged equal, then the will cannot break the deadlock, all it can do is to suspend judgement until the circumstances change, and the right course of action is clear.|Jean Buridan, c. 1340}} \nLater writers satirised this view in terms of an [[donkey|ass]] which, confronted by both food and water, must necessarily die of both hunger and thirst while pondering a decision.\n\n==Discussion==\nSome proponents of [[hard determinism]] have granted the unpleasantness of the scenario, but have denied that it illustrates a true [[paradox]], since one does not [[contradiction|contradict]] oneself in suggesting that a man might die between two equally plausible routes of action. For example, in his ''[[Ethics (Spinoza)|Ethics]]'', [[Benedict de Spinoza]] suggests that a person who sees two options as truly equally compelling cannot be fully rational: {{Quotation|[I]t may be objected, if man does not act from free will, what will happen if the incentives to action are equally balanced, as in the case of Buridan's ass? [In reply,] I am quite ready to admit, that a man placed in the equilibrium described (namely, as perceiving nothing but hunger and thirst, a certain food and a certain drink, each equally distant from him) would die of hunger and thirst. If I am asked, whether such a one should not rather be considered an ass than a man; I answer, that I do not know, neither do I know how a man should be considered, who hangs himself, or how we should consider children, fools, madmen, &c.|[[Baruch Spinoza]]|[[Ethics (Spinoza)|Ethics]], book&nbsp;2, proposition 49, [[scholium]]}}\n\nOther writers{{who|date=September 2014}} have opted to deny the validity of the illustration. A typical{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} counter-argument is that [[rationality]] as described in the paradox is so limited as to be a [[straw man]] version of the real thing, which does allow the consideration of meta-arguments. In other words, it is entirely rational to recognize that both choices are equally good and arbitrarily ([[randomness|randomly]]) pick one instead of starving; although the decision that they are sufficiently the same is also subject to Buridan's ass. The idea that a random decision could be made is sometimes used as an attempted justification for [[faith]] or intuitivity (called by Aristotle noetic or [[noesis]]). The argument is that, like the starving ass, we must make a choice to avoid being frozen in endless doubt. Other counter-arguments exist.{{specify|date=August 2014}}\n\nAccording to Edward Lauzinger, Buridan's ass fails to incorporate the latent biases that humans always bring with them when making decisions.<ref>\"Thought and Process\", Lauzinger, Edward, 1994</ref>{{full|date=July 2013}}\n\n==Buridan's principle==\nThe situation of Buridan's ass was given a mathematical basis in a 1984 paper by American computer scientist [[Leslie Lamport]], in which Lamport presents an argument that, given certain assumptions about [[continuous function|continuity]] in a simple [[mathematical model]] of the Buridan's ass problem, there is always some starting condition under which the ass starves to death, no matter what strategy it takes.<ref name=\"Lamport 1984\">{{cite web|author=Leslie Lamport|url=http://research.microsoft.com/users/lamport/pubs/buridan.pdf|title=Buridan's Principle|date=December 1984|accessdate=2010-07-09}}</ref>  He further illustrates the paradox with the example of a driver stopped at a [[railroad crossing]] trying to decide whether he has time to cross before a train arrives.  He proves that regardless of how \"safe\" the policy the driver adopts, because indecision can cause an indefinite delay in action a small percentage of drivers will be hit by the train.\n\nLamport calls this result \"Buridan\u2019s principle\":<ref name=\"Lamport 1984\" />\n:A discrete decision based upon an input having a continuous range of values cannot be made within a bounded length of time.\n\nHe points out that just because we do not see asses or people starving to death through indecision, or other examples of Buridan's undecided states in real life, does not disprove the principle.  The persistence of a Buridan's undecided state for a perceptible length of time may just be sufficiently improbable that it has not been observed.\n\n==Application to digital logic: metastability==\n{{main|Metastability in electronics}}\nA version of Buridan's principle actually occurs in [[electrical engineering]].<ref name=\"Lamport2\">{{cite web|author=Leslie Lamport|url=http://research.microsoft.com/users/lamport/pubs/buridan.pdf|title=Buridan's Principle|date=December 1984|accessdate=2010-07-09}}, p. 8</ref><ref name=\"Xanthopoulos\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Xanthopoulos\n | first1 = Thucydides \n | title  = Clocking in Modern VLSI Systems\n | publisher = Springer Science & Business Media\n | date   = 2009\n | location = \n | pages  = 191\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=UZZGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA191&dq=buridan\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-1441902610\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Niederman\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Niederman\n | first1 = Derrick \n | title  = The Puzzler's Dilemma\n | publisher = Penguin\n | date   = 2012\n | location = \n | pages  = 130\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=RvhGaqZ_oNUC&pg=PT130&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-1101560877\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Zbilut\">{{cite book\n | last1  =  Zbilut\n | first1 = Joseph P.\n | title  = Unstable Singularities and Randomness\n | publisher = Elsevier\n | date   = 2004\n | location = \n | pages  = 7\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=YVid9QybwbUC&pg=PA7&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22+computer\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 0080474691\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Kinniment2\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Kinniment\n | first1 = David J. \n | title  = Synchronization and Arbitration in Digital Systems\n | publisher = John Wiley & Sons\n | date   = 2008\n | location = \n | pages  = 2\u20136\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=_1p-BA4yriIC&pg=PA2&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0470517130\n }}</ref> Specifically, the input to a [[digital logic]] gate must convert a continuous [[voltage]] value into either a 0 or a 1, which is typically sampled and then processed. If the input is changing and at an intermediate value when sampled, the input stage acts like a [[comparator]]. The voltage value can then be likened to the position of the ass, and the values 0 and 1 represent the bales of hay. As in the situation of the starving ass, there exists an input on which the converter cannot make a proper decision, and the output remains balanced in a [[Metastability in electronics|metastable]] state between the two stable states for an undetermined length of time, until random noise in the circuit makes it converge to one of the stable states.\n\nIn asynchronous circuits [[Arbiter (electronics)|Arbiters]] are used to make the decision. They guarantee that up to one outcome is selected at any given point in time, but may take an indeterminate (albeit typically extremely short) time to choose.<ref name=arbiter>{{cite journal\n|last1       =Sutherland\n|first1      =Ivan E.\n|authorlink1 =Ivan Sutherland\n|last2       =Ebergen\n|first2      =Jo\n|title       =Computers Without Clocks\n|journal     =[[Scientific American]]\n|volume      =287\n|issue       =2\n|date        =August 2002\n|pages       =62\u201369\n|doi =10.1038/scientificamerican0802-62\n|pmid =12140955\n|bibcode =2002SciAm.287b..62S\n}}</ref>\n\nThe metastability problem is a significant issue in [[digital circuit design]], and metastable states are a possibility wherever [[asynchronous circuit|asynchronous]] inputs (digital signals not synchronized to a [[clock signal]]) occur. The ultimate reason the problem is manageable is that the probability of a metastable state persisting longer than a given time interval ''t'' is an exponentially declining function of ''t''. In electronic devices, the probability of such an \"undecided\" state lasting longer than a matter of nanoseconds, while always possible, can be made negligibly low.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*[[Lewis Cass]], the Democratic candidate for president in 1848, was contrasted with Buridan's ass by [[Abraham Lincoln]]:  \"Mr. Speaker, we have all heard of the animal standing in doubt between two stacks of hay, and starving to death.  The like would never happen to General Cass; place the stacks a thousand miles apart, he would stand stock still midway between them, and [[You can't have your cake and eat it|eat them both at once]], and the green grass along the line would be apt to suffer some too at the same time.\"<ref>[[Carl Sandburg]] (1954), ''Abraham Lincoln:  The Prairie Years'', 1960 reprint, New York:  Dell, Vol. 1, Ch. 7, \"Congressman Lincoln\", p. 173.</ref> (This being a reference to Cass's support for [[Popular_sovereignty_in_the_United_States#.22Popular_sovereignty.22_in_the_dispute_over_slavery|\"popular sovereignty\"]] in the [[Origins of the American Civil War|run-up to the Civil War]].)\n*[[Buridan's Donkey (film)|''Buridan's Donkey'']], a 1932 French comedy film, is named after the paradox.\n*\"[[Buridan's Ass (Fargo)|Buridan's Ass]]\" is the name of the sixth episode of the first season of the FX television series ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]''.\n*In the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' novel ''[[The Eight Doctors]]'', the [[Fifth Doctor|Fifth]] and [[Eighth Doctor|Eighth]] Doctors are confronted by a [[List of Doctor Who robots#Raston Warrior Robot|Raston Warrior Robot]]. The Doctors stand exactly the same distance away from the Robot as it approaches them; unable to decide which to attack first (since the Robot attacks by sensing brain patterns, which are identical in the two Doctors), the Robot shuts down.\n*The lyrics of a song by [[Devo]], the title track from their album ''[[Freedom of Choice_(album)|Freedom of Choice]]'', describe a similar situation:  \"In ancient Rome, there was a poem / About a dog who found two bones\" who then, unable to choose between the two, \"went in circles till he dropped dead.\"\n*In [[The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep214|the 10th season]] of ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', Sheldon and Amy discuss the history of Buridan's ass (renamed donkey), and its application to their lives. Amy resolves the paradox (of Sheldon desiring to live in different apartments) by creating a more desirable option by engaging Sheldon in a discussion of the theory and its history.\n*On episode 2 of the 3rd season of [[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]] (Kimmy's Roommate Lemonades), Kimmy learns about Buridan's Ass from Perry, a possible love interest and also a tour guide for prospective students at Robert Moses College for Everyone.\n*In ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'', a note can be found on a notice board from a farmer that is selling the meat of his donkey, who died of starvation because it was unable to decide between two different pile of food,\n*[[Aleksander Fredro]], Polish 19th-century poet, tells a story about a donkey who died from hunger because he could not decide between oats and hay, served in two troughs.\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Analysis paralysis]]\n*[[Catch-22 (logic)|Catch-22]]\n*[[Dining philosophers problem]]\n*[[Hobson's choice]]\n*[[Lagrangian point]]\n*[[Morton's fork]]\n*{{slink|Principle of sufficient reason|Leibniz's view}}\n*[[Search cost]]\n*[[Spontaneous symmetry breaking]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |title=The Columbia Encyclopedia |year=2006 |edition=6th }}\n*{{cite book |author=Knowles, Elizabeth |title=The Oxford Dictionary of Phrase and Fable |year=2006 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Mawson, T.J. |title=Belief in God |publisher=Oxford University (Clarendon) Press |location=New York, NY |year=2005 |page=201 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=Rescher, Nicholas |title=Choice Without Preference: A Study of the History and of the Logic of the Problem of 'Buridan's Ass' |journal=Kant-Studien |volume=51 |issue=1\u20134 |pages=142\u201375 |year=1959 |doi=10.1515/kant.1960.51.1-4.142 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Zupko, Jack |title=John Buridan: Portrait of a Fourteenth-Century Arts Master |publisher=University of Notre Dame Press |location=Notre Dame, Indiana |year=2003 |pages=258, 400n71 }}\n*{{cite journal |first=E. |last=Ullmann-Margalit |first2=S. |last2=Morgenbesser |title=Picking and Choos-ing |journal=Social Research |volume=44 |issue= |year=1977 |pages=757\u2013785 |jstor= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite journal |author=Vassiliy Lubchenko |title=Competing interactions create functionality through frustration |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=105 |issue=31 |pages=10635\u20136 |date=August 2008 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/105/31/10635.full |doi=10.1073/pnas.0805716105 |pmid=18669666 |pmc=2504771|bibcode=2008PNAS..10510635L }}\n\n{{Decision theory paradoxes}}\n\n[[Category:Decision-making paradoxes]]\n[[Category:Fictional donkeys]]\n[[Category:Thought experiments in philosophy]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Deliberations of Congress.jpg|thumb|Political cartoon c.&nbsp;1900, showing the [[United States Congress]] as Buridan's ass (the two hay piles version), hesitating between a [[Panama Canal|Panama route]] or a [[Nicaragua Canal|Nicaragua route]] for an [[History of the Panama Canal|Atlantic\u2013Pacific canal]].]]\n\n'''Buridan's ass''' is an illustration of a [[paradox]] in philosophy in the conception of [[free will]].\nIt refers to a hypothetical situation wherein a [[donkey]] that is equally hungry and thirsty is placed precisely midway between a stack of hay and a pail of water. Since the paradox assumes the ass will always go to whichever is closer, it dies of both hunger and thirst since it cannot make any rational decision between the hay and water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O214-Buridansass.html |title=Buridan's ass: Oxford Companion to Phrase and Fable |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=2009-12-15}}</ref> A common variant of the paradox substitutes two identical piles of hay for the hay and water; the ass, unable to choose between the two, dies of hunger.\n\nThe paradox is named after the 14th-century [[France|French]] [[philosopher]] [[Jean Buridan]], whose philosophy of moral [[determinism]] it satirizes. \nAlthough the illustration is named after Buridan, philosophers have discussed the concept before him, notably [[Aristotle]] who used the example of a man equally hungry and thirsty,<ref name=\"Rescher\" /> and [[Al-Ghazali]] who used a man faced with the choice of equally good [[date (fruit)|dates]].<ref name=Kane/>\n\nA version of this situation appears as [[metastability in electronics|metastability]] in digital electronics, when a circuit must decide between two states based on an input that is in itself undefined (neither zero nor one).  Metastability becomes a problem if the circuit spends more time than it should in this \"undecided\" state, which is usually set by the speed of the clock the system is using.\n\n==History==\n\nThe paradox predates Buridan; it dates to antiquity, being found in [[Aristotle]]'s ''[[On the Heavens]]''.<ref name=\"Rescher\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Rescher\n  | first = Nicholas \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Cosmos and Logos: Studies in Greek Philosophy\n  | publisher = Ontos Verlag\n  | date = 2005\n  | location = \n  | pages = 93\u201399\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=qU3MdvVlvpAC&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=aristotle+%22buridan's+ass%22#v=onepage&q=aristotle%20%22buridan's%20ass%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 393720265X}}</ref>  Aristotle, in ridiculing the [[Sophist]] idea that the Earth is stationary simply because it is spherical and any forces on it must be equal in all directions, says that is as ridiculous as saying that:<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n{{Quotation|...a man, being just as hungry as thirsty, and placed in between food and drink, must necessarily remain where he is and starve to death.|Aristotle, ''On the Heavens'' 295b, c. 350 BC }}\nHowever, the Greeks only used this paradox as an analogy in the context of the equilibrium of ''physical'' forces.<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n\nThe 12th century Persian scholar and philosopher [[al-Ghazali]] discusses the application of this paradox to human decision making, asking whether it is possible to make a choice between equally good courses without grounds for preference.<ref name=\"Rescher\" /> He takes the attitude that free will can break the stalemate.\n{{Quotation|Suppose two similar dates in front of a man, who has a strong desire for them but who is unable to take them both. Surely he will take one of them, through a quality in him, the nature of which is to differentiate between two similar things.|[[Al-Ghazali|Abu Hamid al-Ghazali]], ''[[The Incoherence of the Philosophers]]'', c.  1100<ref name=Kane>{{cite book |last=Kane |first=Robert |title=A Contemporary Introduction to Free Will |year=2005 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York|pages=37}}</ref>}}\nMoorish philosopher [[Averroes]] (1126\u20131198), in commentary on Ghazali, takes the opposite view.<ref name=\"Rescher\" />\n\nAlthough Buridan nowhere discusses this specific problem, its relevance is that he did advocate a moral determinism whereby, save for ignorance or impediment, a human faced by alternative courses of action must always choose the greater [[good (economics)|good]]. In the face of equally good alternatives Buridan believed a rational choice could not be made.<ref name=\"Kinniment\">{{cite book     | last = Kinniment  | first = David J.   | authorlink =   | title = Synchronization and Arbitration in Digital Systems  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons  | date = 2008  | location =   | pages = 3  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_1p-BA4yriIC&pg=PA3\n  | doi =   | isbn = 978-0470517130}}</ref> \n{{Quotation|Should two courses be judged equal, then the will cannot break the deadlock, all it can do is to suspend judgement until the circumstances change, and the right course of action is clear.|Jean Buridan, c. 1340}} \nLater writers satirised this view in terms of an [[donkey|ass]] which, confronted by both food and water, must necessarily die of both hunger and thirst while pondering a decision.\n\n==Discussion==\nSome proponents of [[hard determinism]] have granted the unpleasantness of the scenario, but have denied that it illustrates a true [[paradox]], since one does not [[contradiction|contradict]] oneself in suggesting that a man might die between two equally plausible routes of action. For example, in his ''[[Ethics (Spinoza)|Ethics]]'', [[Benedict de Spinoza]] suggests that a person who sees two options as truly equally compelling cannot be fully rational: {{Quotation|[I]t may be objected, if man does not act from free will, what will happen if the incentives to action are equally balanced, as in the case of Buridan's ass? [In reply,] I am quite ready to admit, that a man placed in the equilibrium described (namely, as perceiving nothing but hunger and thirst, a certain food and a certain drink, each equally distant from him) would die of hunger and thirst. If I am asked, whether such a one should not rather be considered an ass than a man; I answer, that I do not know, neither do I know how a man should be considered, who hangs himself, or how we should consider children, fools, madmen, &c.|[[Baruch Spinoza]]|[[Ethics (Spinoza)|Ethics]], book&nbsp;2, proposition 49, [[scholium]]}}\n\nOther writers{{who|date=September 2014}} have opted to deny the validity of the illustration. A typical{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} counter-argument is that [[rationality]] as described in the paradox is so limited as to be a [[straw man]] version of the real thing, which does allow the consideration of meta-arguments. In other words, it is entirely rational to recognize that both choices are equally good and arbitrarily ([[randomness|randomly]]) pick one instead of starving; although the decision that they are sufficiently the same is also subject to Buridan's ass. The idea that a random decision could be made is sometimes used as an attempted justification for [[faith]] or intuitivity (called by Aristotle noetic or [[noesis]]). The argument is that, like the starving ass, we must make a choice to avoid being frozen in endless doubt. Other counter-arguments exist.{{specify|date=August 2014}}\n\nAccording to Edward Lauzinger, Buridan's ass fails to incorporate the latent biases that humans always bring with them when making decisions.<ref>\"Thought and Process\", Lauzinger, Edward, 1994</ref>{{full|date=July 2013}}\n\n==Buridan's principle==\nThe situation of Buridan's ass was given a mathematical basis in a 1984 paper by American computer scientist [[Leslie Lamport]], in which Lamport presents an argument that, given certain assumptions about [[continuous function|continuity]] in a simple [[mathematical model]] of the Buridan's ass problem, there is always some starting condition under which the ass starves to death, no matter what strategy it takes.<ref name=\"Lamport 1984\">{{cite web|author=Leslie Lamport|url=http://research.microsoft.com/users/lamport/pubs/buridan.pdf|title=Buridan's Principle|date=December 1984|accessdate=2010-07-09}}</ref>  He further illustrates the paradox with the example of a driver stopped at a [[railroad crossing]] trying to decide whether he has time to cross before a train arrives.  He proves that regardless of how \"safe\" the policy the driver adopts, because indecision can cause an indefinite delay in action a small percentage of drivers will be hit by the train.\n\nLamport calls this result \"Buridan\u2019s principle\":<ref name=\"Lamport 1984\" />\n:A discrete decision based upon an input having a continuous range of values cannot be made within a bounded length of time.\n\nHe points out that just because we do not see asses or people starving to death through indecision, or other examples of Buridan's undecided states in real life, does not disprove the principle.  The persistence of a Buridan's undecided state for a perceptible length of time may just be sufficiently improbable that it has not been observed.\n\n==Application to digital logic: metastability==\n{{main|Metastability in electronics}}\nA version of Buridan's principle actually occurs in [[electrical engineering]].<ref name=\"Lamport2\">{{cite web|author=Leslie Lamport|url=http://research.microsoft.com/users/lamport/pubs/buridan.pdf|title=Buridan's Principle|date=December 1984|accessdate=2010-07-09}}, p. 8</ref><ref name=\"Xanthopoulos\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Xanthopoulos\n | first1 = Thucydides \n | title  = Clocking in Modern VLSI Systems\n | publisher = Springer Science & Business Media\n | date   = 2009\n | location = \n | pages  = 191\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=UZZGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA191&dq=buridan\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-1441902610\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Niederman\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Niederman\n | first1 = Derrick \n | title  = The Puzzler's Dilemma\n | publisher = Penguin\n | date   = 2012\n | location = \n | pages  = 130\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=RvhGaqZ_oNUC&pg=PT130&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-1101560877\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Zbilut\">{{cite book\n | last1  =  Zbilut\n | first1 = Joseph P.\n | title  = Unstable Singularities and Randomness\n | publisher = Elsevier\n | date   = 2004\n | location = \n | pages  = 7\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=YVid9QybwbUC&pg=PA7&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22+computer\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 0080474691\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Kinniment2\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Kinniment\n | first1 = David J. \n | title  = Synchronization and Arbitration in Digital Systems\n | publisher = John Wiley & Sons\n | date   = 2008\n | location = \n | pages  = 2\u20136\n | language = \n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=_1p-BA4yriIC&pg=PA2&dq=%22buridan%27s+ass%22\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0470517130\n }}</ref> Specifically, the input to a [[digital logic]] gate must convert a continuous [[voltage]] value into either a 0 or a 1, which is typically sampled and then processed. If the input is changing and at an intermediate value when sampled, the input stage acts like a [[comparator]]. The voltage value can then be likened to the position of the ass, and the values 0 and 1 represent the bales of hay. As in the situation of the starving ass, there exists an input on which the converter cannot make a proper decision, and the output remains balanced in a [[Metastability in electronics|metastable]] state between the two stable states for an undetermined length of time, until random noise in the circuit makes it converge to one of the stable states.\n\nIn asynchronous circuits [[Arbiter (electronics)|Arbiters]] are used to make the decision. They guarantee that up to one outcome is selected at any given point in time, but may take an indeterminate (albeit typically extremely short) time to choose.<ref name=arbiter>{{cite journal\n|last1       =Sutherland\n|first1      =Ivan E.\n|authorlink1 =Ivan Sutherland\n|last2       =Ebergen\n|first2      =Jo\n|title       =Computers Without Clocks\n|journal     =[[Scientific American]]\n|volume      =287\n|issue       =2\n|date        =August 2002\n|pages       =62\u201369\n|doi =10.1038/scientificamerican0802-62\n|pmid =12140955\n|bibcode =2002SciAm.287b..62S\n}}</ref>\n\nThe metastability problem is a significant issue in [[digital circuit design]], and metastable states are a possibility wherever [[asynchronous circuit|asynchronous]] inputs (digital signals not synchronized to a [[clock signal]]) occur. The ultimate reason the problem is manageable is that the probability of a metastable state persisting longer than a given time interval ''t'' is an exponentially declining function of ''t''. In electronic devices, the probability of such an \"undecided\" state lasting longer than a matter of nanoseconds, while always possible, can be made negligibly low.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*[[Lewis Cass]], the Democratic candidate for president in 1848, was contrasted with Buridan's ass by [[Abraham Lincoln]]:  \"Mr. Speaker, we have all heard of the animal standing in doubt between two stacks of hay, and starving to death.  The like would never happen to General Cass; place the stacks a thousand miles apart, he would stand stock still midway between them, and [[You can't have your cake and eat it|eat them both at once]], and the green grass along the line would be apt to suffer some too at the same time.\"<ref>[[Carl Sandburg]] (1954), ''Abraham Lincoln:  The Prairie Years'', 1960 reprint, New York:  Dell, Vol. 1, Ch. 7, \"Congressman Lincoln\", p. 173.</ref> (This being a reference to Cass's support for [[Popular_sovereignty_in_the_United_States#.22Popular_sovereignty.22_in_the_dispute_over_slavery|\"popular sovereignty\"]] in the [[Origins of the American Civil War|run-up to the Civil War]].)\n*[[Buridan's Donkey (film)|''Buridan's Donkey'']], a 1932 French comedy film, is named after the paradox.\n*\"[[Buridan's Ass (Fargo)|Buridan's Ass]]\" is the name of the sixth episode of the first season of the FX television series ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]''.\n*In the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' novel ''[[The Eight Doctors]]'', the [[Fifth Doctor|Fifth]] and [[Eighth Doctor|Eighth]] Doctors are confronted by a [[List of Doctor Who robots#Raston Warrior Robot|Raston Warrior Robot]]. The Doctors stand exactly the same distance away from the Robot as it approaches them; unable to decide which to attack first (since the Robot attacks by sensing brain patterns, which are identical in the two Doctors), the Robot shuts down.\n*The lyrics of a song by [[Devo]], the title track from their album ''[[Freedom of Choice_(album)|Freedom of Choice]]'', describe a similar situation:  \"In ancient Rome, there was a poem / About a dog who found two bones\" who then, unable to choose between the two, \"went in circles till he dropped dead.\"\n*In [[The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep214|the 10th season]] of ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', Sheldon and Amy discuss the history of Buridan's ass (renamed donkey), and its application to their lives. Amy resolves the paradox (of Sheldon desiring to live in different apartments) by creating a more desirable option by engaging Sheldon in a discussion of the theory and its history.\n*On episode 2 of the 3rd season of [[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]] (Kimmy's Roommate Lemonades), Kimmy learns about Buridan's Ass from Perry, a possible love interest and also a tour guide for prospective students at Robert Moses College for Everyone.\n*In ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'', a note can be found on a notice board from a farmer that is selling the meat of his donkey, who died of starvation because it was unable to decide between two different pile of food,\n*[[Aleksander Fredro]], Polish 19th-century poet, tells a story about a donkey who died from hunger because he could not decide between oats and hay, served in two troughs.\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Analysis paralysis]]\n*[[Catch-22 (logic)|Catch-22]]\n*[[Dining philosophers problem]]\n*[[Hobson's choice]]\n*[[Lagrangian point]]\n*[[Morton's fork]]\n*{{slink|Principle of sufficient reason|Leibniz's view}}\n*[[Search cost]]\n*[[Spontaneous symmetry breaking]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |title=The Columbia Encyclopedia |year=2006 |edition=6th }}\n*{{cite book |author=Knowles, Elizabeth |title=The Oxford Dictionary of Phrase and Fable |year=2006 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Mawson, T.J. |title=Belief in God |publisher=Oxford University (Clarendon) Press |location=New York, NY |year=2005 |page=201 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=Rescher, Nicholas |title=Choice Without Preference: A Study of the History and of the Logic of the Problem of 'Buridan's Ass' |journal=Kant-Studien |volume=51 |issue=1\u20134 |pages=142\u201375 |year=1959 |doi=10.1515/kant.1960.51.1-4.142 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Zupko, Jack |title=John Buridan: Portrait of a Fourteenth-Century Arts Master |publisher=University of Notre Dame Press |location=Notre Dame, Indiana |year=2003 |pages=258, 400n71 }}\n*{{cite journal |first=E. |last=Ullmann-Margalit |first2=S. |last2=Morgenbesser |title=Picking and Choos-ing |journal=Social Research |volume=44 |issue= |year=1977 |pages=757\u2013785 |jstor= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite journal |author=Vassiliy Lubchenko |title=Competing interactions create functionality through frustration |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=105 |issue=31 |pages=10635\u20136 |date=August 2008 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/105/31/10635.full |doi=10.1073/pnas.0805716105 |pmid=18669666 |pmc=2504771|bibcode=2008PNAS..10510635L }}\n\n{{Decision theory paradoxes}